Cathay, Henderson, Sun Hung Kai: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-10-04T00:54:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-04/cathay-henderson-sun-hung-kai-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 4.4 percent to 16,822.15. The Hang
Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, declined 5.7 percent to 8,408.26.  Airlines: Airline profits forecast to total $28 billion in
the three years through 2012 may be unsustainable as over-
capacity and looming regulatory costs weigh on margins, the head
of the IATA industry association said.  Cathay Pacific Airways Ltd. (293)  (293 HK),  Asia ’s largest
international carrier, slid 3.9 percent to HK$12.30. China
Southern Airlines Co. (1055 HK), Asia’s largest carrier by
passenger numbers, declined 6.3 percent to HK$3.45.  China 
Eastern Airlines Corp. (670 HK), the No. 2, retreated 9.7
percent to HK$2.24.  Developers: Hong Kong’s housing prices may be in a bubble,
and could repeat the collapse that occurred during the Asian
financial crisis,  Fitch Ratings  said.  Fitch affirmed its ratings on Hong Kong’s debt, citing a
prudent fiscal policy held by the city government and
“resilience” in the economy supported by competitiveness of
the services sector, according to a statement yesterday.  Henderson Land Development Co. (12 HK), the builder
controlled by billionaire Lee Shau-kee, slid 4 percent to
HK$34.05.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK): Malls operated by the
world’s No. 1 developer by market value drew 1.8 million
shoppers amounting to HK$64 million ($8.22 million) in sales on
the first two days of the Golden Week, the Standard reported,
citing Senior Promotions Manager Eric Lau. The stock fell 1.7
percent to HK$88.90.  Bank of East Asia Ltd. (23)  (23 HK): Hong Leong Investment
Holdings Pte bought 2.01 million shares of Bank of  East Asia  at
an average price of HK$26.651 apiece on Sept. 23, according to a
statement to the Hong Kong stock exchange. Bank of East Asia,
Hong Kong’s third-largest lender by market value, plunged 7.5
percent to HK$22.35.  Shanghai Pharmaceuticals Holding Co. (2607 HK): China’s
drug distributor is actively looking for “sizeable” merger and
acquisition opportunities to strengthen its product portfolio
and market presence, Credit Suisse Group AG said. The stock
tumbled 7.6 percent to HK$15.68.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Hong Kong at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
 John McCluskey  at 
 j.mccluskey@bloomberg.net . 